INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '5b3ca69a-4e3f-4e05-bd89-1ac86ddc430e',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Angular Forms — Reactive vs Template-Driven, and Wiring Zod for Schema Validation$escape$,
  $escape$Angular offers two form strategies: template-driven (uncontrolled-style — `ngModel` drives state in the template) and reactive (controlled-style — `FormGroup`/`FormControl` live in the component class). For validation-heavy forms, reactive wins. Angular 14's strictly-typed reactive forms (`FormGroup<{email: FormControl<string>}>`) catch field-name typos and shape mismatches at compile time.

To replicate the React Hook Form + Zod pattern, wire a Zod schema directly into Angular's validator pipeline. Write a `zodValidator()` factory that calls `schema.safeParse(ctrl.value)` and maps failures to `ValidationErrors`. Pass per-field schema slices via `schema.shape.email` — this co-locates validation rules with the schema, keeps the component class free of `if/else` guard logic, and gives you typed error objects renderable in templates via `control.errors?.['zod']`.

Template-driven forms still fit simple UIs with minimal validation — avoid reactive boilerplate when two-way `ngModel` binding is sufficient.$escape$,
  $escape$import { z } from 'zod';
import { AbstractControl, ValidationErrors, FormControl, FormGroup } from '@angular/forms';

const loginSchema = z.object({
  email: z.string().email(),
  age: z.number().min(18),
});

function zodValidator(schema: z.ZodTypeAny) {
  return (ctrl: AbstractControl): ValidationErrors | null => {
    const result = schema.safeParse(ctrl.value);
    return result.success ? null : { zod: result.error.flatten() };
  };
}

const form = new FormGroup({
  email: new FormControl('', zodValidator(loginSchema.shape.email)),
  age: new FormControl(0, zodValidator(loginSchema.shape.age)),
});$escape$,
