INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '44337f06-e60a-4605-83af-5242cef2bc36',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Angular Code Quality — @angular-eslint Rules, Naming Conventions, and the 50-Line Method Rule$escape$,
  $escape$Angular's `@angular-eslint` package brings component-aware static analysis that generic ESLint rules miss. The `component-selector` and `directive-selector` rules enforce Angular's style guide at lint time: components must use element selectors with a kebab-case prefix (`app-user-card`), while directives use attribute-style camelCase (`appHighlight`). Violations surface as CI failures instead of silent runtime mismatches.

`@angular-eslint/no-empty-lifecycle-method` removes noise from scaffolded stubs — empty `ngOnInit()` or `ngOnDestroy()` bodies add reviewer overhead and signal incomplete implementations. Pair it with `@angular-eslint/use-lifecycle-interface`: Angular requires explicit interface declarations (`implements OnInit`) to catch hook typos at compile time. Without the interface, a misspelled `ngOnlnit()` silently never runs.

For the 50-line rule, add `max-lines-per-function` at 50 to your ESLint config. OnPush components frequently bloat inside `ngOnInit` with combined data fetching, subscription wiring, and state initialization. When the rule fires, it's a signal to extract fetching into a dedicated `load()` private method or push initialization logic into a route resolver — keeping each lifecycle hook to a single, auditable responsibility.$escape$,
  $escape$// .eslintrc.json (inside @angular-eslint rules block)
{
  "@angular-eslint/component-selector": ["error", {
    "type": "element", "prefix": "app", "style": "kebab-case"
  }],
  "@angular-eslint/directive-selector": ["error", {
    "type": "attribute", "prefix": "app", "style": "camelCase"
  }],
  "@angular-eslint/no-empty-lifecycle-method": "error",
  "@angular-eslint/use-lifecycle-interface": "error",
  "max-lines-per-function": ["warn", { "max": 50, "skipBlankLines": true }]
}$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
