INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'd7c6cd6e-fd2a-4fb1-82a9-cc7364e79cbb',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Angular Web Vitals — How Component Patterns Break LCP, CLS, and INP$escape$,
  $escape$Angular's component decisions have a direct line to your Core Web Vitals scores.

**LCP:** Use the `NgOptimizedImage` directive (`[ngSrc]`) — it auto-generates `srcset`, sets `fetchpriority="high"` when you add `priority`, and enforces `width`/`height` attributes. Never wrap above-the-fold images in `@defer`; deferred blocks sit behind a JS-triggered fetch boundary and will crater LCP.

**CLS:** `@if` blocks that toggle after an async resolve are CLS traps. The DOM insertion shifts surrounding content unless you pre-reserve space with `min-height` on the container, or render an unconditional skeleton. `ViewContainerRef.createComponent()` dynamic insertions carry the same risk — size the host element before the component lands.

**INP:** Angular's default `ChangeDetectionStrategy.Default` runs a full Zone.js dirty-check on every DOM event. Switching to `OnPush` + Angular Signals narrows detection to explicit signal writes. For scroll or resize handlers that never mutate view state, call `NgZone.runOutsideAngular()` — this removes the event entirely from Zone tracking and routinely cuts INP by 40–60 ms on event-dense components.$escape$,
  $escape$// LCP — prioritize hero image with NgOptimizedImage
<img ngSrc="hero.webp" width="1200" height="600" priority />

// CLS — reserve space before @if resolves
<div style="min-height: 200px">
  @if (card()) { <app-card [data]="card()" /> }
</div>

// INP — escape Zone.js for non-view listeners
@Component({ changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush })
export class FeedComponent {
  constructor(private ngZone: NgZone) {
    ngZone.runOutsideAngular(() => {
      window.addEventListener('scroll', this.handleScroll);
    });
  }
}$escape$,
