INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '90109249-f1bf-485b-891f-9a58bb450f55',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Angular Quality Gates — Prettier, Husky + lint-staged, and tsc --noEmit in CI$escape$,
  $escape$Angular projects ship with ESLint via `ng add @angular-eslint/schematics`, but formatting and pre-commit enforcement require extra wiring. Add Prettier alongside it, then configure Husky + lint-staged to gate every commit: lint-staged runs `eslint --fix` and `prettier --write` only on staged `.ts` and `.html` files — critical for Angular's two-file component pattern where template linting is separate from TS linting.

In CI, never rely on `ng build` alone to catch type errors — it skips checking lazy-loaded modules by default. Run `tsc --noEmit -p tsconfig.app.json` explicitly to surface type errors across the full project graph, including standalone components and signal-based inputs introduced in Angular 17+.

Pair this with `ng lint` in your GitHub Actions workflow as a separate step. The combination — Prettier on commit, ESLint on commit, `tsc --noEmit` + `ng lint` in CI — creates a layered gate that catches formatting drift, template binding errors, and type regressions before they reach main.$escape$,
  $escape$# .lintstagedrc.json
{
  "*.ts": ["eslint --fix", "prettier --write"],
  "*.html": ["prettier --write", "eslint --fix"]
}

# GitHub Actions step (ci.yml)
- name: Type check
  run: npx tsc --noEmit -p tsconfig.app.json

- name: Lint
  run: npx ng lint$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
